<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<entry xmlns:functx="http://www.functx.com" xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"
    xml:id="entry_dyzærdyg" xml:lang="os">
    <form xml:lang="os-x-iron" type="lemma"><orth>dyzærdyg</orth></form>
    <form xml:lang="os-x-digor" type="dialectal"><orth>duzærdug</orth></form>
    <sense><sense><cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
                <q>сомнение</q>
            </cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <q>doubt</q>
            </cit></sense><sense><cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
                <q>колебание</q>
            </cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <q>hesitation</q>
            </cit></sense><sense><cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
                <q>сомневающийся</q>
            </cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <q>doubtful</q>
            </cit></sense><sense><cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
                <q>колеблющийся</q>
            </cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <q>hesitating</q>
            </cit></sense></sense>
    <etym xml:lang="ru">Буквально „двусердие“; см. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_dy-"/> | %idu%i и
            <ref type="xr" target="#entry_zærdæ"/> ‘сердце’. Ср. <mentioned xml:lang="fa"
                ><lang/><w>dödil</w><gloss><q>сомневающийся</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned
            xml:lang="fa"><w/><gloss><q>колеблющийся</q></gloss></mentioned>, , буквально
        „двусердый“. Такое же образование, но с иным значением, в грузинском: <mentioned
            xml:lang="ka"><lang/><w>orguli</w><gloss><q>вероломный</q></gloss></mentioned> из
            <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/><w>ori</w><gloss><q>два</q></gloss></mentioned> и
            <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/><w>guli</w><gloss><q>сердце</q></gloss></mentioned>. —
        Ср. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_īwzærdyg"/>.%n<bibl><ref target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."
                /><biblScope>48, 90</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
    <etym xml:lang="en">Literally “double-heartness”; see <ref type="xr" target="#entry_dy-"/> |
        %idu%i and <ref type="xr" target="#entry_zærdæ"/> ‘heary’. Ср. <mentioned xml:lang="fa"
                ><lang/><w>dödil</w><gloss><q>doubtful</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned
            xml:lang="fa"><w/><gloss><q>hesitating</q></gloss></mentioned>, , literally “two
        hearted”. The same derivative but with another meaning is found in Georgian: <mentioned
            xml:lang="ka"><lang/><w>orguli</w><gloss><q>faithless</q></gloss></mentioned> from
            <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/><w>ori</w><gloss><q>two</q></gloss></mentioned> and
            <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/><w>guli</w><gloss><q>heart</q></gloss></mentioned>. —
        Cf. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_īwzærdyg"/>.%n<bibl><ref target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."
                /><biblScope>48, 90</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
</entry>
